    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor: ''The Season for Sea Turtles'' (June 8) brought back the treasured memory of a rare experience I shared with my then 5-year-old son and my parents 17 years ago.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor: ''The Season for Sea Turtles'' (June 8) brought back the treasured memory of a rare experience I shared with my then 5-year-old son and my parents 17 years ago.</p>
        <p>One evening at the Gumbo Limbo Environmental Complex in Boca Raton, Fla., a group of us listened to an educational talk and then received the thrilling radio transmission from a scout on the beach that a turtle had been sighted. After arriving at the location, we formed a circle and watched in silence as she lumbered up the beach, dug a hole and began laying her eggs. The entire time tears poured out of her eyes. Back then we were allowed to take pictures once the egg laying began, and I treasure mine. After the last egg was laid, the turtle covered the nest with sand, made her way back to the ocean and disappeared into the vast black expanse.</p>
        <p>Linda K. Friedman  Mendham, N.J.</p>
      </block>
